{"title_page": "William Priestley (St Mawes MP)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n'''William Priestley''' (c.1594&ndash;1664) was a lawyer and member of the [[Long Parliament]], the son of William Priestley (d.1620), a [[Worshipful Company of Merchant Taylors|merchant tailor]] in the [[City of London]]. \n \nPriestley was admitted to [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge|Sidney College, Cambridge]], 18 April 1610, and was admitted to [[Gray's Inn|the Honourable Society of Gray's Inn]], 4 August 1612.<ref>The register of admissions to Gray\u2019s Inn (London 1889), 130.</ref>  Following his father's death in 1620, Priestley inherited Camfield House in Essendon;<ref>Will of William Preistley, Merchant Tailor of London, 1620, TNA PROB 11/135/649; Chancery: Inquisitions Post Mortem; TNA C 142/385/34.</ref> then, in 1627, he acquired  the manor of Bedwell Lowthes.  The family lived in a house known as Wyldehelle or Weald Hill, on the border of [[Hatfield, Hertfordshire|Hatfield]] and [[Essendon, Hertfordshire|Essendon]].<ref>When Priestley\u2019s grandson, was admitted to Gray\u2019s Inn, 11 November 1686, he is described: William, son & heir of Thomas Priestley of Weald Hill, Hertfordshire.  The register of admissions to Gray\u2019s Inn (London 1889), 338.</ref>\n\nPriestley was appointed [[High Sheriff of Hertfordshire]] in 1634.<ref>Clutterbuck, Robert, The history and antiquities of Hertfordshire (London, 1861), 129.</ref>  In 1647, during the [[Long Parliament]], William Priestley was appointed as a [[Recruiter elections (Seventeenth-century by-elections)|Recruiter]] MP for [[St Mawes (UK Parliament constituency)|St Mawes in Cornwall]], to fill the vacancy caused by the expulsion of the [[English Civil War|Royalist]] [[George Parry (MP)|Dr George Parry]] who had been expelled in January 1644.  Priestley himself was cast out of the [[House of Commons of England|House]], along with his colleague, the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] Richard Erisey, during [[Pride's Purge]], December 1648.\nWilliam Priestley died 10 March 1663/4.<ref>Clutterbuck, ''op.cit.'', 135.</ref>  There is a large monument to him, on the south aisle wall of the parish church.<ref>'Parishes: Essendon', ''A History of the County of Hertford'': volume 3 (1912), pp. 458-462. URL: http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43641.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Priestley, William}}\n[[Category:English lawyers]]\n[[Category:1594 births]]\n[[Category:1664 deaths]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640\u20131648]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:17th-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Welwyn Hatfield (district)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n'''William Priestley''' (c.1594&ndash;1664) was a lawyer and member of the [[Long Parliament]], the son of William Priestley (d.1620), a [[Worshipful Company of Merchant Taylors|merchant tailor]] in the [[City of London]]. \n \nPriestley was admitted to [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge|Sidney College, Cambridge]], 18 April 1610, and was admitted to [[Gray's Inn|the Honourable Society of Gray\u2019s Inn]], 4 August 1612.<ref>The register of admissions to Gray\u2019s Inn (London 1889), 130.</ref>  Following his father\u2019s death in 1620, Priestley inherited Camfield House in Essendon;<ref>Will of William Preistley, Merchant Tailor of London, 1620, TNA PROB 11/135/649; Chancery: Inquisitions Post Mortem; TNA C 142/385/34.</ref> then, in 1627, he acquired  the manor of Bedwell Lowthes.  The family lived in a house known as Wyldehelle or Weald Hill, on the border of [[Hatfield, Hertfordshire|Hatfield]] and [[Essendon, Hertfordshire|Essendon]].<ref>When Priestley\u2019s grandson, was admitted to Gray\u2019s Inn, 11 November 1686, he is described: William, son & heir of Thomas Priestley of Weald Hill, Hertfordshire.  The register of admissions to Gray\u2019s Inn (London 1889), 338.</ref>\n\nPriestley was appointed [[High Sheriff of Hertfordshire]] in 1634.<ref>Clutterbuck, Robert, The history and antiquities of Hertfordshire (London, 1861), 129.</ref>  In 1647, during the [[Long Parliament]], William Priestley was appointed as a [[Recruiter elections (Seventeenth-century by-elections)|Recruiter]] MP for [[St Mawes (UK Parliament constituency)|St Mawes in Cornwall]], to fill the vacancy caused by the expulsion of the [[English Civil War|Royalist]] [[George Parry (MP)|Dr George Parry]] who had been expelled in January 1644.  Priestley himself was cast out of the [[House of Commons of England|House]], along with his colleague, the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] Richard Erisey, during [[Pride's Purge]], December 1648.\nWilliam Priestley died 10 March 1663/4.<ref>Clutterbuck, ''op.cit.'', 135.</ref>  There is a large monument to him, on the south aisle wall of the parish church.<ref>'Parishes: Essendon', ''A History of the County of Hertford'': volume 3 (1912), pp. 458-462. URL: http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43641.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Priestley, William}}\n[[Category:English lawyers]]\n[[Category:1594 births]]\n[[Category:1664 deaths]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640\u20131648]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:17th-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Welwyn Hatfield (district)]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Priestley_(St_Mawes_MP)"}
{"title_page": "Public Warning", "text_new": "{{short description|2006 album by Lady Sovereign}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Public Warning\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Lady Sovereign]]\n| cover      = Ladysovereign_publicwarning.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2006|10|31}}\n| recorded   = 2004\u20132006\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Grime (music)|Grime]]\n*[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n*[[electronica]]\n}}\n| length     = 44:27\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Lady Sovereign]] <small>([[Executive producer#Music|exec.]])</small>\n*[[Basement Jaxx]]\n*[[Dr. Luke]]\n*[[Gabriel Prokofiev|Medasyn]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Blah Blah (album)|Blah Blah]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Jigsaw (Lady Sovereign album)|Jigsaw]]\n| next_year  = 2009\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Public Warning\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Random (Lady Sovereign song)|Random]]\n | single1date = 14 March 2005\n | single2     = [[9 to 5 (Lady Sovereign song)|9 to 5]]\n | single2date = 8 August 2005\n | single3     = [[Hoodie (Lady Sovereign song)|Hoodie]]\n | single3date = 21 November 2005\n | single4     = [[Love Me or Hate Me]]\n | single4date = 30 October 2006\n | single5     = [[Those Were the Days (Lady Sovereign song)|Those Were the Days]]\n | single5date = 9 April 2007\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Public Warning''''' is the first [[studio album]] by English [[hip hop music|hip hop]] artist [[Lady Sovereign]], released on 31 October 2006. Was originally due for release in November 2005 but was pushed back after Lady Sovereign was signed by [[Island Def Jam]].\n\nIn a July 2006 press release, the album's track listing was confirmed. ''Public Warning'' features Lady Sovereign's three past singles, tracks from her two [[extended play|EP]]s: ''[[Vertically Challenged (EP)|Vertically Challenged]]'' and ''[[Blah Blah (album)|Blah Blah]]'', as well as newly recorded tracks for the release, including \"[[Love Me or Hate Me]]\" and \"[[Those Were the Days (Lady Sovereign song)|Those Were the Days]]\". The album was released in the U.K. on 5 February 2007, with a live cover of the [[Sex Pistols]]' \"[[Pretty Vacant]]\" as a bonus track.\n\n''Public Warning'' received generally positive reviews from critics, who praised the production and lyrical content for carrying both humor and substance. The album sold over 125,000 copies in the United States <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266142/lady-sovereign-starts-label-preps-album|publisher=Billboard|title=Lady Sovereign Starts Label, Preps Album|first=Jonathan|last=Cohen||date=12 August 2008|accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> and sold 250,000 copies worldwide. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/can-celebrity-big-brother-save-lady-sovereigns-career-782293|publisher=NME|title=Can Celebrity Big Brother Save Lady Sovereign\u2019s Career?|first=Talia|last=Sogohomnian||date=4 January 2010|accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 67/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/ladysovereign/publicwarning | title=Reviews for Public Warning by Lady Sovereign | website=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=7 April 2009 }}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/public-warning-mw0000555886|title=Public Warning \u2013 Lady Sovereign|last=Jeffries|first=David|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = B+<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/lady-sovereign-empublic-warningem-8080|title=Review: Lady Sovereign: Public Warning|last=Matos|first=Michaelangelo|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|date=14 November 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev3Score = 8/10<ref name=\"DiS\">{{cite magazine|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/9144/reviews/1595624-|title=Album Review: Lady Sovereign \u2013 Public Warning|last=Diver|first=Mike|magazine=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=7 February 2007|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1551456,00.html|title=Public Warning|last=Endelman|first=Michael|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=27 October 2006|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/feb/02/urban.shopping|title=CD: Lady Sovereign, Public Warning|last=Macpherson|first=Alex|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=2 February 2007|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 6.4/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/9582-public-warning/|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning!|last=Dombal|first=Ryan|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=1 November 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/lady-sovereign-public-warning/|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning|last=Raper|first=Dan|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|date=16 October 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/ladysovereign/albums/album/12056662/review/12060155/public_warning|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning|last=Hsu|first=Hua|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=18 October 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015|archivedate=11 February 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211155506/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/ladysovereign/albums/album/12056662/review/12060155/public_warning|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev9 = [[Slant Magazine]]\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/lady-sovereign-public-warning|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning|last=Jones|first=Preston|magazine=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=24 October 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Stylus Magazine]]\n| rev10Score = D+<ref name=\"Stylus\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/lady-sovereign/public-warning.htm|title=Lady Sovereign \u2013 Public Warning! \u2013 Review|last=Shipley|first=Al|magazine=[[Stylus Magazine]]|date=7 November 2006|accessdate=8 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112135820/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/lady-sovereign/public-warning.htm|archivedate=12 November 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n''Public Warning'' received generally positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album has received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 67, based on 34 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\n[[AllMusic]] editor David Jeffries praised the album for Medasyn's production and Sovereign's lyrical content for being relatable, calling it \"an exciting introduction to an extraordinary artist captured at just the right time.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> Michaelangelo Matos of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' compared the album to [[The Sex Pistols]], praising tracks like \"Tango\" and \"Hoodie\" for their angst-filled energy, saying \"Even if Sov doesn't cross over the way she or Def Jam might want her to, she still sounds like an original\u2014even for people who know half the songs already.\"<ref name=\"AVClub\"/> Mike Diver of [[Drowned in Sound]] praised the album for having solid production and lyrical content that's both gritty and humorous, saying \"When her tongue's in cheek and her rhymes amuse, Lady Sovereign is hugely entertaining.\"<ref name=\"DiS\"/>\n\nMichael Endelman of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' found criticism in the album's overly frenetic beats and out-of-tune choruses but praised Sovereign for her humor and lyrical flow, saying that her \"rubbery rhymes and punky energy are definitely entertaining, and well worth sampling in moderate doses.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> Steve 'Flash' Juon of ''RapReviews'' commented that Sovereign's heavily accented lyrics and electronic beats can get abrasive at times but said the album has crossover potential because of her flow and humor that requires little British familiarity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2006_11_publicwarning.html|title=Lady Sovereign :: Public Warning :: Def Jam|last=Juon|first=Steve 'Flash'|website=RapReviews|date=7 November 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe album also received negative reception from critics. Alex Macpherson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented on Sovereign's talent being wasted on hollow content and production that moved towards ska-punk than grime, calling it \"the sound of a fantastic artist seemingly intent on compromising all her strengths.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Baz Dreisinger of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' compared Sovereign to [[Eminem]], commenting on the catchy choruses, juvenile humor and one-liners throughout the album but felt that it lacked character and substance to match the comparison.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2006-10-31/music/pint-sized-tea-shunning-femme-mc-cleans-out-her-closet/|title=Pint-Sized, Tea-Shunning Femme MC Cleans Out Her Closet|last=Dreisinger|first=Baz|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=31 October 2006|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> The most critical of the album was Al Shipley of [[Stylus Magazine]], who heavily criticized the botched humor, synthpop production and Sovereign's lyrical flow, saying that she \"simulates the altogether new and horrible experience of hearing [[Eliza Doolittle]] rap.\"<ref name=\"Stylus\"/>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked the album number 48 on its list of Best Albums of 2006.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.stereogum.com/4165/rolling_stones_best_albums_of_06/franchises/list/|title=''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s Best Albums Of '06|author=Stereogum Staff|magazine=[[Stereogum]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|date=14 December 2006|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Censored version==\nA censored version was also released that used backmasking and sound effects over the profanities. The album booklet still has all the lyrics written out, but the profanities are starred over.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title1 = [[9 to 5 (Lady Sovereign song)|9 to 5]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Louise Harman]]|Gabriel Olegavich}}\n| extra1 = Medasyn\n| length1 = 3:32\n| title2 = Gatheration\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich|Danny Harrison|Arthur Smith}}\n| extra2 = Menta\n| length2 = 3:23\n| title3 = [[Random (Lady Sovereign song)|Random]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich|Harrison|Smith}}\n| extra3 = Menta\n| length3 = 3:36\n| title4 = Public Warning\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra4 = Medasyn\n| length4  = 3:46\n| title5 = [[Love Me or Hate Me]]\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Harman|[[Lukasz Gottwald]]}}\n| extra5 = [[Dr. Luke]]\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = My England\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra6 = Medasyn\n| length6 = 3:57\n| title7 = Tango\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra7 = Medasyn\n| length7 = 3:37\n| title8 = A Little Bit of Shhh\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra8 = Medasyn\n| length8 = 3:45\n| title9 = [[Hoodie (Lady Sovereign song)|Hoodie]]\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra9 = Medasyn\n| length9 = 3:37\n| title10 = [[Those Were the Days (Lady Sovereign song)|Those Were the Days]]\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Harman|Gottwald}}\n| extra10 = Dr Luke\n| length10 = 3:50\n| title11 = Blah Blah\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra11 = [[Basement Jaxx]]\n| length11 = 3:57\n| title12 = Fiddle with the Volume\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra12 = Medasyn\n| length12 = 3:37\n| title13 = [[Love Me or Hate Me]]\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Harman|Gottwald|[[Missy Elliott]]}}\n| note13 = Remix featuring [[Missy Elliott]]\n| extra13 = Dr Luke\n| length13 = 3:38\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = [[iTunes Store|iTunes]] bonus tracks\n| title14 = Pretty Vacant (Live at Commodore Ballroom)\n| length14 = 3:38\n| title15 = The Broom\n| length15 = 4:02\n| title16 = Hoodie ([[Mizz Beats]] Remix)\n| note16 = feat. [[Skepta]], [[JME (rapper)|JME]], [[Jammer (rapper)|Jammer]], Ears & Baby Blue)\n| length16 = 4:07\n| title17 = 9 to 5 ([[The Ordinary Boys]] Remix)\n| length17 = 3:25\n}}\n\n* The enhanced CD contains a link to a 15-minute documentary\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2006)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australiian Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20061220-0000/issue874.pdf|title=Public Warning ARIA album chart|publisher=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|97\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Japan Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/414094/products/music/693336/1/|title=\u30d1\u30d6\u30ea\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30a6\u30a9\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0 - \u30ec\u30c7\u30a3\u30fc\u30fb\u30bd\u30f4\u30a1\u30ea\u30f3|publisher=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|212\n|-\n{{album chart|UK|58|artist=Lady Sovereign|accessdate=21 September 2008}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|48|artist=Lady Sovereign|artistid=306357|accessdate=21 September 2008}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRap|12|artist=Lady Sovereign|artistid=306357|accessdate=21 September 2008}}\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Region\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Format\n! scope=\"col\" | Label\n|-\n| United States<ref name=\"iTunesUS\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/public-warning/id201855439|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Public Warning by Lady Sovereign|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n| 31 October 2006\n| Digital download, CD\n| rowspan=\"4\"|[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n|-\n| United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Public-Warning-Vinyl-Lady-Sovereign/dp/B000KP7JAE|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning [Vinyl]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n| 12 December 2006\n| Vinyl\n|-\n| United Kingdom\n| 5 February 2007\n| Digital download, CD\n|-\n| Germany<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.de/Public-Warning-Lady-Sovereign/dp/B000IFRQAY |title=Public Warning - Lady Sovereign |website=Amazon.de |language=German |accessdate=20 August 2018}}</ref>\n| 30 March 2007\n| Digital download, CD\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Lady Sovereign}}\n\n[[Category:2006 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Lady Sovereign albums]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dr. Luke]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2006 album by Lady Sovereign}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Public Warning\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Lady Sovereign]]\n| cover      = Ladysovereign_publicwarning.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2006|10|31}}\n| recorded   = 2004\u20132006\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Grime (music)|Grime]]\n*[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n*[[electronica]]\n}}\n| length     = 44:27\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Lady Sovereign]] <small>([[Executive producer#Music|exec.]])</small>\n*[[Basement Jaxx]]\n*[[Dr. Luke]]\n*[[Gabriel Prokofiev|Medasyn]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Blah Blah (album)|Blah Blah]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Jigsaw (Lady Sovereign album)|Jigsaw]]\n| next_year  = 2009\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Public Warning\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Random (Lady Sovereign song)|Random]]\n | single1date = 14 March 2005\n | single2     = [[9 to 5 (Lady Sovereign song)|9 to 5]]\n | single2date = 8 August 2005\n | single3     = [[Hoodie (Lady Sovereign song)|Hoodie]]\n | single3date = 21 November 2005\n | single4     = [[Love Me or Hate Me]]\n | single4date = 30 October 2006\n | single5     = [[Those Were the Days (Lady Sovereign song)|Those Were the Days]]\n | single5date = 9 April 2007\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Public Warning''''' is the first [[studio album]] by English [[hip hop music|hip hop]] artist [[Lady Sovereign]], released on 31 October 2006. Was originally due for release in November 2005 but was pushed back after Lady Sovereign was signed by [[Island Def Jam]].\n\nIn a July 2006 press release, the album's track listing was confirmed. ''Public Warning'' features Lady Sovereign's three past singles, tracks from her two [[extended play|EP]]s: ''[[Vertically Challenged (EP)|Vertically Challenged]]'' and ''[[Blah Blah (album)|Blah Blah]]'', as well as newly recorded tracks for the release, including \"[[Love Me or Hate Me]]\" and \"[[Those Were the Days (Lady Sovereign song)|Those Were the Days]]\". The album was released in the U.K. on 5 February 2007, with a live cover of the [[Sex Pistols]]' \"[[Pretty Vacant]]\" as a bonus track.\n\n''Public Warning'' received generally positive reviews from critics, who praised the production and lyrical content for carrying both humor and substance. The album sold over 125,000 copies in the United States <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266142/lady-sovereign-starts-label-preps-album|publisher=Billboard|title=Lady Sovereign Starts Label, Preps Album|first=Jonathan|last=Cohen||date=12 August 2008|accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> and sold 250,000 copies worldwide. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/can-celebrity-big-brother-save-lady-sovereigns-career-782293|publisher=NME|title=Can Celebrity Big Brother Save Lady Sovereign\u2019s Career?|first=Talia|last=Sogohomnian||date=4 January 2010|accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 67/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/ladysovereign/publicwarning | title=Reviews for Public Warning by Lady Sovereign | website=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=7 April 2009 }}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/public-warning-mw0000555886|title=Public Warning \u2013 Lady Sovereign|last=Jeffries|first=David|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = B+<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/lady-sovereign-empublic-warningem-8080|title=Review: Lady Sovereign: Public Warning|last=Matos|first=Michaelangelo|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|date=14 November 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev3Score = 8/10<ref name=\"DiS\">{{cite magazine|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/9144/reviews/1595624-|title=Album Review: Lady Sovereign \u2013 Public Warning|last=Diver|first=Mike|magazine=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=7 February 2007|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1551456,00.html|title=Public Warning|last=Endelman|first=Michael|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=27 October 2006|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/feb/02/urban.shopping|title=CD: Lady Sovereign, Public Warning|last=Macpherson|first=Alex|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=2 February 2007|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 6.4/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/9582-public-warning/|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning!|last=Dombal|first=Ryan|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=1 November 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/lady-sovereign-public-warning/|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning|last=Raper|first=Dan|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|date=16 October 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/ladysovereign/albums/album/12056662/review/12060155/public_warning|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning|last=Hsu|first=Hua|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=18 October 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015|archivedate=11 February 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211155506/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/ladysovereign/albums/album/12056662/review/12060155/public_warning|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev9 = [[Slant Magazine]]\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/lady-sovereign-public-warning|title=Lady Sovereign: Public Warning|last=Jones|first=Preston|magazine=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=24 October 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Stylus Magazine]]\n| rev10Score = D+<ref name=\"Stylus\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/lady-sovereign/public-warning.htm|title=Lady Sovereign \u2013 Public Warning! \u2013 Review|last=Shipley|first=Al|magazine=[[Stylus Magazine]]|date=7 November 2006|accessdate=8 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112135820/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/lady-sovereign/public-warning.htm|archivedate=12 November 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n''Public Warning'' received generally positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album has received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 67, based on 34 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\n[[AllMusic]] editor David Jeffries praised the album for Medasyn's production and Sovereign's lyrical content for being relatable, calling it \"an exciting introduction to an extraordinary artist captured at just the right time.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> Michaelangelo Matos of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' compared the album to [[The Sex Pistols]], praising tracks like \"Tango\" and \"Hoodie\" for their angst-filled energy, saying \"Even if Sov doesn't cross over the way she or Def Jam might want her to, she still sounds like an original\u2014even for people who know half the songs already.\"<ref name=\"AVClub\"/> Mike Diver of [[Drowned in Sound]] praised the album for having solid production and lyrical content that's both gritty and humorous, saying \"When her tongue's in cheek and her rhymes amuse, Lady Sovereign is hugely entertaining.\"<ref name=\"DiS\"/>\n\nMichael Endelman of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' found criticism in the album's overly frenetic beats and out-of-tune choruses but praised Sovereign for her humor and lyrical flow, saying that her \"rubbery rhymes and punky energy are definitely entertaining, and well worth sampling in moderate doses.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> Steve 'Flash' Juon of ''RapReviews'' commented that Sovereign's heavily accented lyrics and electronic beats can get abrasive at times but said the album has crossover potential because of her flow and humor that requires little British familiarity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2006_11_publicwarning.html|title=Lady Sovereign :: Public Warning :: Def Jam|last=Juon|first=Steve 'Flash'|website=RapReviews|date=7 November 2006|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe album also received negative reception from critics. Alex Macpherson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented on Sovereign's talent being wasted on hollow content and production that moved towards ska-punk than grime, calling it \"the sound of a fantastic artist seemingly intent on compromising all her strengths.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Baz Dreisinger of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' compared Sovereign to [[Eminem]], commenting on the catchy choruses, juvenile humor and one-liners throughout the album but felt that it lacked character and substance to match the comparison.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2006-10-31/music/pint-sized-tea-shunning-femme-mc-cleans-out-her-closet/|title=Pint-Sized, Tea-Shunning Femme MC Cleans Out Her Closet|last=Dreisinger|first=Baz|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=31 October 2006|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> The most critical of the album was Al Shipley of [[Stylus Magazine]], who heavily criticized the botched humor, synthpop production and Sovereign's lyrical flow, saying that she \"simulates the altogether new and horrible experience of hearing [[Eliza Doolittle]] rap.\"<ref name=\"Stylus\"/>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked the album number 48 on its list of Best Albums of 2006.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.stereogum.com/4165/rolling_stones_best_albums_of_06/franchises/list/|title=''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s Best Albums Of '06|author=Stereogum Staff|magazine=[[Stereogum]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|date=14 December 2006|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Censored version==\nA censored version was also released that used backmasking and sound effects over the profanities. The album booklet still has all the lyrics written out, but the profanities are starred over.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title1 = [[9 to 5 (Lady Sovereign song)|9 to 5]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Louise Harman]]|Gabriel Olegavich}}\n| extra1 = Medasyn\n| length1 = 3:32\n| title2 = Gatheration\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich|Danny Harrison|Arthur Smith}}\n| extra2 = Menta\n| length2 = 3:23\n| title3 = [[Random (Lady Sovereign song)|Random]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich|Harrison|Smith}}\n| extra3 = Menta\n| length3 = 3:36\n| title4 = Public Warning\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra4 = Medasyn\n| length4  = 3:46\n| title5 = [[Love Me or Hate Me]]\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Harman|[[Lukasz Gottwald]]}}\n| extra5 = [[Dr. Luke]]\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = My England\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra6 = Medasyn\n| length6 = 3:57\n| title7 = Tango\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra7 = Medasyn\n| length7 = 3:37\n| title8 = A Little Bit of Shhh\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra8 = Medasyn\n| length8 = 3:45\n| title9 = [[Hoodie (Lady Sovereign song)|Hoodie]]\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra9 = Medasyn\n| length9 = 3:37\n| title10 = [[Those Were the Days (Lady Sovereign song)|Those Were the Days]]\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Harman|Gottwald}}\n| extra10 = Dr Luke\n| length10 = 3:50\n| title11 = Blah Blah\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra11 = [[Basement Jaxx]]\n| length11 = 3:57\n| title12 = Fiddle with the Volume\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Harman|Olegavich}}\n| extra12 = Medasyn\n| length12 = 3:37\n| title13 = [[Love Me or Hate Me]]\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Harman|Gottwald|[[Missy Elliott]]}}\n| note13 = Remix featuring [[Missy Elliott]]\n| extra13 = Dr Luke\n| length13 = 3:38\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = [[iTunes Store|iTunes]] bonus tracks\n| title14 = Pretty Vacant (Live at Commodore Ballroom)\n| length14 = 3:38\n| title15 = The Broom\n| length15 = 4:02\n| 