\u0631\u0627\u0646|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baamardom.ir/113619/\u0627\u0646\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0628-\u0633\u0641\u06cc\u0631-\u06a9\u0648\u062f\u06a9\u0627\u0646-\u06a9\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0646-\u0633\u0646\u062f\u0631\u0648\u0645-\u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646/|title=\u0627\u0646\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0628 \u0633\u0641\u06cc\u0631 \u06a9\u0648\u062f\u06a9\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0633\u0646\u062f\u0631\u0648\u0645 \u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646|date=2018-01-14|website=\u0628\u0627\u0645\u0631\u062f\u0645 {{!}} \u0627\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646 {{!}} \u067e\u0627\u06cc\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u062e\u0628\u0631\u06cc \u062a\u062d\u0644\u06cc\u0644\u06cc \u0628\u0627 \u0645\u0631\u062f\u0645 \u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646|language=fa-IR|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>. She also elected as a face of the year 2019 by people in [[Gilan Province]], for her social activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aparat.com/v/OK293/%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86_%D9%86%DB%8C%DA%A9%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%87_%DA%86%D9%87%D8%B1%D9%87_%D8%B3%D8%A7%D9%84_%DA%AF%DB%8C%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86_%D8%AF%D8%B1_%DA%AF%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%87_%D9%81%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%DB%8C%D8%AA%26zwnj%3B%D9%87%D8%A7%DB%8C_%D8%A7%D8%AC%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B9%DB%8C|title=\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0646\u06cc\u06a9\u0631\u0627\u0647 \u0686\u0647\u0631\u0647 \u0633\u0627\u0644 \u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u0631 \u06af\u0631\u0648\u0647 \u0641\u0639\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u062a\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u0627\u062c\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc|website=\u0622\u067e\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a - \u0633\u0631\u0648\u06cc\u0633 \u0627\u0634\u062a\u0631\u0627\u06a9 \u0648\u06cc\u062f\u06cc\u0648|language=fa|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gilanmedia.com/%d8%a8%d8%a7%d8%b1%d8%a7%d9%86-%d9%86%db%8c%da%a9%d8%b1%d8%a7%d9%87-%da%86%d9%87%d8%b1%d9%87-%d8%b3%d8%a7%d9%84-%da%af%db%8c%d9%84%d8%a7%d9%86-%d8%af%d8%b1-%da%af%d8%b1%d9%88%d9%87-%d9%81%d8%b9%d8%a7/|title=\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0646\u06cc\u06a9\u0631\u0627\u0647 \u0686\u0647\u0631\u0647 \u0633\u0627\u0644 \u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u0631 \u06af\u0631\u0648\u0647 \u0641\u0639\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u062a\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u0627\u062c\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc|website=\u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u062f\u06cc\u0627 {{!}} Gilan Media|language=fa-IR|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zamintv.com/v/2kp6z78g|title=\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0646\u06cc\u06a9\u0631\u0627\u0647 \u0686\u0647\u0631\u0647 \u0633\u0627\u0644 \u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u0631 \u06af\u0631\u0648\u0647 \u0641\u0639\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u062a\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u0627\u062c\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc - \u0632\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u062a\u06cc \u0648\u06cc|website=\u0632\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u062a\u06cc \u0648\u06cc  - \u0633\u0631\u0648\u06cc\u0633 \u0627\u0634\u062a\u0631\u0627\u06a9 \u0648\u06cc\u062f\u06cc\u0648|language=fa|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nShe started her activities as a host presenter accidentally while at the University of Gilan (where she was a student), the main presenter could not make it and she went on the stage (around 2008). Since then, she takes it as her profession, and as a host presenter, she managed several international festivals, events, and TV-Radio programs. Following are her activities in various fields:\n\n=== As TV, stage and seminar host and presenter ===\n\n* Fanavarane Danesh program in [[IRIB TV4]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jamejamonline.ir/fa/news/1101211|title=\u00ab\u0641\u0646\u0627\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u0627\u0646\u0634\u00bb \u0628\u0647 \u0634\u0628\u06a9\u0647 \u0686\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0645\u06cc \u0622\u06cc\u0646\u062f|last=\u0622\u0646\u0644\u0627\u06cc\u0646|first=\u062c\u0627\u0645 \u062c\u0645|date=\u06f1\u06f3\u06f9\u06f6/\u06f0\u06f9/\u06f1\u06f9 - \u06f1\u06f7:\u06f1\u06f5|website=fa|language=fa|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n* Melody Harekat show<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khabargozarisaba.com/16196/\u0645\u0644\u0648\u062f\u06cc-\u062d\u0631\u06a9\u062a-\u0628\u0627-\u0627\u062c\u0631\u0627\u06cc-\u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646-\u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646\u06cc-\u0631\u0648\u06cc-\u0635\u062d\u0646\u0647-\u0645\u06cc-\u0631\u0648\u062f/|title=\u00ab\u0645\u0644\u0648\u062f\u06cc \u062d\u0631\u06a9\u062a\u00bb \u0628\u0627 \u0627\u062c\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0631\u0648\u06cc \u0635\u062d\u0646\u0647 \u0645\u06cc \u0631\u0648\u062f {{!}} \u062e\u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0635\u0628\u0627|website=www.khabargozarisaba.com|language=fa-IR|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n* Silk Road Research seminar in Rasht<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kalanshahr.ir/news/451|title=- \u0633\u0645\u06cc\u0646\u0627\u0631 \u067e\u0698\u0648\u0647\u0634\u06cc \u062c\u0627\u062f\u0647 \u0627\u0628\u0631\u06cc\u0634\u0645\u061b \u0634\u0647\u0631 \u062e\u0644\u0627\u0642 \u0631\u0634\u062a \u0648 \u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af \u062e\u0648\u0631\u0627\u06a9|website=\u067e\u0627\u06cc\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u062e\u0628\u0631\u06cc \u06a9\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0634\u0647\u0631 {{!}} \u0627\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u06af\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646 \u0648 \u0631\u0634\u062a|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n* Conference in honor of Mirza Kuchak Khan Jangali<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gilkhabar.ir/news/328280|title=- \u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635\u06cc/ \u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0634 \u062a\u0635\u0648\u06cc\u0631\u06cc \u0647\u0645\u0627\u06cc\u0634 \u0628\u0632\u0631\u06af\u062f\u0627\u0634\u062a \u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627 \u06a9\u0648\u0686\u06a9 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u0646\u06af\u0644\u06cc \u0628\u0627 \u0633\u062e\u0646\u0631\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0631\u0626\u06cc\u0633 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0634\u0648\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc|website=\u06af\u06cc\u0644 \u062e\u0628\u0631|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n* 1st Conference of Woman and Health Culture in Rasht<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diyarmirza.ir/1397/10/\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0634-\u062a\u0635\u0648\u06cc\u0631\u06cc-\u0646\u062e\u0633\u062a\u06cc\u0646-\u0647\u0645\u0627\u06cc\u0634-\u0632\u0646-\u0648-\u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af-\u0633\u0644/|title=\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0634 \u062a\u0635\u0648\u06cc\u0631\u06cc \u0646\u062e\u0633\u062a\u06cc\u0646 \u0647\u0645\u0627\u06cc\u0634 \u0632\u0646 \u0648 \u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af \u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u062a \u062f\u0631 \u0631\u0634\u062a|language=fa|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.instagram.com/baran_nikrah/?hl=en Baran Nikrah] - Instagram profile\n\n{{iran-tv-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iranian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Iranian radio presenters]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baran_Nikrah"}
{"title_page": "Al-Jiftlik", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Al-Jiftlik\n| translit_lang1          = Arabic\n| translit_lang1_type     = [[Arabic script|Arabic]]\n| translit_lang1_info     = \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0641\u062a\u0644\u0643\n| translit_lang1_type1    = [[Latin script|Latin]]\n| translit_lang1_info1    = Al-Jeftlik (official)<br />El-Jeftlak (unofficial)\n| type                    = [[Village council (Palestinian Authority)|Municipality type D (Village council)]]\n| image_skyline           = UNRWA's Ghor El Far'a school in Al-Jiftlik 143 - Aug 2011.jpg\n| image_caption           = UNRWA school in al-Jiftlik, 2011\n| pushpin_map             = Palestine\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Al-Jiftlik within [[State of Palestine|Palestine]]\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|32|08|39|N|35|29|36|E|region:PS|display=inline,title}}\n| grid_name               = [[Palestine grid|Palestine&nbsp;grid]]\n| grid_position           = 196/172\n| subdivision_type        = State\n| subdivision_name        = [[State of Palestine]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Governorates of the Palestinian National Authority|Governorate]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Jericho Governorate|Jericho]]\n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = \n| government_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| government_type         = [[Village council (Palestinian Authority)|Village council]] \n| leader_title            = Head of Municipality\n| leader_name             = Muhammad Omar [[Jahalin Bedouin|Jahalin]]<ref>[http://www.elections.ps/pdf/Municipal_Elections_Results_EN_(2).pdf West Bank] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630094514/http://www.elections.ps/pdf/Municipal_Elections_Results_EN_%282%29.pdf |date=2007-06-30 }} Local Elections ( Round two)- Successful candidates by local authority, gender and No. of votes obtained, al-Jftalak p 23</ref>\n| unit_pref               = dunam\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 185.0\n| area_total_dunam        = 185032\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| elevation_min_m         = \n| elevation_max_m         = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 3,546\n| population_as_of        = 2007\n| population_note         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Al-Jiftlik''' ({{lang-ar|<big>\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0641\u062a\u0644\u0643</big>}}) is a [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] village in the [[Jericho Governorate]] in the [[West Bank]], located 33 kilometers north of [[Jericho]]. Al  Jiftlik is  bordered  by the  Jordan  River to  the  east. Nearby Palestinian localities include [[az-Zubaidat]] to the northeast, [[Furush Beit Dajan]] to the northwest, [[Beit Furik]] to the west, [[Aqraba, Nablus|Aqraba]], [[Majdal Bani Fadil]] and [[Duma, Nablus|Duma]] to the southwest and [[al-Fasayil]] to the south.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>  According to the [[Palestinian Central Bureau of Statistics]] (PCBS), al-Jiftlik had a population of 3,546 in the 2007 census.\n\nThe village's total area amounts to 185,032 [[dunam]]s, of which 972 dunams are Palestinian built up areas, 77 are for commercial and industrial transport units, 64,032 are arable lands and 108,606 dunams are open spaces. Israeli settlements, including [[Massua]], [[Hamra, Bik'at HaYarden|Hamra]] and [[Argaman]] and military bases account for 11,293 dunams.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/> The remaining land consists of forests and inland water.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe majority of the land in al-Jiftlik belonged to the al-Masa'id tribe, a powerful [[Bedouin]] family whose land spanned from [[City of Adam|Damia]] in [[Transjordan (region)|Transjordan]], on the east bank of the [[Jordan River]], to the borders of Jericho in the West Bank. Most of its residents are descendants of the al-Masa'id tribe and immigrants from [[Tammun]] to the north.<ref name=\"ARIJ\">[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/vprofile/Al%20Jiftlik_en_FINAL.pdf Al Jiftlik Village Profile]. [[Applied Research Institute-Jerusalem]] (ARIJ). 2012.</ref>\n\nThe village's name is derived from the [[Turkish language|Turkish]] word ''[[Chiflik (Ottoman Empire)|chiflik]]'', the term for \"land tenure\" in the late [[Ottoman Empire]] which was applied in this as in many other Ottoman locations.<ref name=\"Eini486\"/> It received its name due to the agricultural nature of the village.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/> During the [[Mandatory Palestine|mandate period]], there was a [[Tegart fort]] known as the Jiftlik Police Post just west of the present village.<ref name=\"Eini486\">{{cite book | author = Roza El-Eini | title = Mandated landscape : British imperial rule in Palestine, 1929-1948 | page = 486 | isbn = 978-0-7146-5426-3 | publisher = Routledge | year = 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]], and after the [[1949 Armistice Agreements]], al-Jiftlik came under [[Jordan|Jordanian]] rule. It was [[Jordanian annexation of the West Bank|annexed by Jordan]] in 1950.\n\nSince the [[Six-Day War]] in 1967,  Al-Jiftlik has been under [[Israeli occupation of the West Bank|Israeli occupation]]. In the aftermath of the war over 800 homes in al-Jiftlik were razed by the [[Israel Defense Forces|Israeli army]] and its 6,000 inhabitants were ordered to leave. Most of al-Jiftlik's inhabitants, however, returned to the village.<ref>[[Ghada Karmi|Karmi, Ghada]] (1999). ''The Palestinian Exodus, 1948-1998''. [[University of London]], Centre of Islamic and Middle Eastern Law. Garnet & Ithaca Press. p.90. {{ISBN|0-86372-244-X}}.</ref> \n\nAfter the [[Oslo II Accord|1995 Accords]]  between the Israel and the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] (PLO), the village was designated as part of [[West Bank Areas in the Oslo II Accord#Area C|Area C]]. This makes it subject to full [[State of Israel|Israeli]] military and civil administration.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/> This has allowed the Israelis to commit what  [[Robert Fisk]] in 2010 called \"ethnic cleansing via bureaucracy\". According to the head of the village council in Jiftlik, Palestinian requests for building were denied or delayed for years, and anything built without permission was \"ruthlessly\" torn down by the Israelis.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/in-the-west-banks-stony-hills-palestine-is-slowly-dying-1883669.html In the West Bank's stony hills, Palestine is slowly dying In the richest of the Occupied lands, Israeli bureaucracy is driving Palestinians out of their homes.] Robert Fisk, [[The Independent]], 30 January 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2005 a [[village council (Palestinian Authority)|village council]] was established to administer local affairs. Its nine members are appointed by the Palestinian National Authority. The council maintains a permanent headquarters and owns a waste collection vehicle. Among its responsibilities are building water and electricity networks in al-Jiftlik and providing an ambulance for the village.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>\n\n==Land confiscations by Israel==\nAccording to [[Applied Research Institute\u2013Jerusalem|ARIJ]], Israel has confiscated land from Al-Jiftlik in order to construct several [[Israeli settlement]]s:\n*2,209 [[dunam]]s for [[Masua]],<ref name=ARIJ17>[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/vprofile/Al%20Jiftlik_en_FINAL.pdf Al Jiftlik Village Profile] p. 17, ARIJ</ref>\n*1,464 dunams for [[Ma'ale Efrayim]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*1,294 dunams for [[Yafit]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*645 dunams for [[Argaman]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*514 dunams for [[Gitit, Bik'at HaYarden|Gitit]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*438 dunams for [[Mekhora]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*176 dunams for [[Petza'el]].<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn the 2007 census al-Jiftlik had a population of 3,546 with exactly 50% being males and the other 50% females. The total number of households was 578 who lived in 692 housing units. The principal clans in al-Jiftlik are the 'Arab al-Masa'id, [[Jahalin Bedouin|'Arab al-Jahalin]], 'Arab al-Ayed, al-Ajajrah, Abu Sureis, Abu Dalakh, Abu Dheila, al-Annuz, al-Rutimat and al-Nafei'at. According to the [[Applied Research Institute-Jerusalem]] (ARIJ), about 100 families have left al-Jiftlik since the start of the [[Second Intifada]] in 2000.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>\n\n==Economy and education==\nLike several other villages in the Jordan Valley area, al-Jiftlik is subject to Israeli restrictions on construction and movement, and most often requests for building permits are denied. The village lacks electricity and water infrastructure.<ref>[http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=555337 Aid agencies tread gingerly in Area C]. ''[[Ma'an News Agency]]''. 2013-1-13.</ref> It has primary school managed by the [[United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East|UNRWA]] with 950 students.\n\n==Id'eis==\nId'eis is a Palestinian community several kilometres south of Al-Jiftlik, close to the Masua Israeli settlement. In May 2014, there were 23 families in two neighboring compounds made up of 13 families consisting of 75 people in 15 residential structures living in the north-west compound and 10 families consisting of 53 people living in 14 tents in the southern compound. Each compound also has many livestock structures for their flocks of several thousand sheep and goats. The community makes its living from shepherding and settled in the present location in 1982 having left the Hebron area and migrated across the Jordan Valley as they searched for pastureland. On 21 May 2014, the southern compound was demolished by five Israeli Civil Administration bulldozers supported by IDF soldiers and Border Police on the basis that the families did not have building permits.<ref name=b20140529>{{cite web|title=Civil Administration demolishes nearly half the homes in community of Id\u2019eis, the Jordan Valley|url=http://www.btselem.org/planning_and_building/20140529_demolition_in_ideis_community|publisher=B'tselem|date=29 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.palestinecrops.ps/articleen.aspx?ano=9 Photo of dates grown at Al-Jiftlik on the Palestine Crops website]\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/factsheet/Al%20Jiftlik_FS_EN.pdf Al Jiftlik Village (Fact Sheet)],(Fact Sheet)],  [[Applied Research Institute - Jerusalem]] (ARIJ)\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/vprofile/Al%20Jiftlik_en_FINAL.pdf Al Jiftlik Village Profile], ARIJ\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/images/english/Al-jiftlik_ap_en.jpg Al Jiftlik Arial photo], ARIJ\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/needsfordevelopment/Jiftlik_N_EN.pdf Locality Development Priorities and Needs in Jiftlik], ARIJ\n*Survey of Western Palestine, Map 15:   [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8377  IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.15.jpg Wikimedia commons]\n\n{{Jericho Governorate}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jiftlik, Al-}}\n[[Category:Jericho Governorate]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1950]]\n[[Category:Villages in the West Bank]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of the State of Palestine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Al-Jiftlik\n| translit_lang1          = Arabic\n| translit_lang1_type     = [[Arabic script|Arabic]]\n| translit_lang1_info     = \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0641\u062a\u0644\u0643\n| translit_lang1_type1    = [[Latin script|Latin]]\n| translit_lang1_info1    = Al-Jeftlik (official)<br />El-Jeftlak (unofficial)\n| type                    = [[Village council (Palestinian Authority)|Municipality type D (Village council)]]\n| image_skyline           = UNRWA's Ghor El Far'a school in Al-Jiftlik 143 - Aug 2011.jpg\n| image_caption           = UNRWA school in al-Jiftlik, 2011\n| pushpin_map             = Palestine\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Al-Jiftlik within [[State of Palestine|Palestine]]\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|32|08|39|N|35|29|36|E|region:PS|display=inline,title}}\n| grid_name               = [[Palestine grid|Palestine&nbsp;grid]]\n| grid_position           = 196/172\n| subdivision_type        = State\n| subdivision_name        = [[State of Palestine]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Governorates of the Palestinian National Authority|Governorate]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Jericho Governorate|Jericho]]\n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = \n| government_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| government_type         = [[Village council (Palestinian Authority)|Village council]] \n| leader_title            = Head of Municipality\n| leader_name             = Muhammad Omar [[Jahalin Bedouin|Jahalin]]<ref>[http://www.elections.ps/pdf/Municipal_Elections_Results_EN_(2).pdf West Bank] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630094514/http://www.elections.ps/pdf/Municipal_Elections_Results_EN_%282%29.pdf |date=2007-06-30 }} Local Elections ( Round two)- Successful candidates by local authority, gender and No. of votes obtained, al-Jftalak p 23</ref>\n| unit_pref               = dunam\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 185.0\n| area_total_dunam        = 185032\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| elevation_min_m         = \n| elevation_max_m         = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 3,546\n| population_as_of        = 2007\n| population_note         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Al-Jiftlik''' ({{lang-ar|<big>\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0641\u062a\u0644\u0643</big>}}) is a [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] village in the [[Jericho Governorate]] in the [[West Bank]], located 33 kilometers north of [[Jericho]]. Al  Jiftlik is  bordered  by the  Jordan  River to  the  east. Nearby Palestinian localities include [[az-Zubaidat]] to the northeast, [[Furush Beit Dajan]] to the northwest, [[Beit Furik]] to the west, [[Aqraba, Nablus|Aqraba]], [[Majdal Bani Fadil]] and [[Duma, Nablus|Duma]] to the southwest and [[al-Fasayil]] to the south.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>  According to the [[Palestinian Central Bureau of Statistics]] (PCBS), al-Jiftlik had a population of 3,546 in the 2007 census.\n\nThe village's total area amounts to 185,032 [[dunam]]s, of which 972 dunams are Palestinian built up areas, 77 are for commercial and industrial transport units, 64,032 are arable lands and 108,606 dunams are open spaces. Israeli settlements, including [[Massua]], [[Hamra, Bik'at HaYarden|Hamra]] and [[Argaman]] and military bases account for 11,293 dunams.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/> The remaining land consists of forests and inland water.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe majority of the land in al-Jiftlik belonged to the al-Masa'id tribe, a powerful [[Bedouin]] family whose land spanned from [[City of Adam|Damia]] in [[Transjordan (region)|Transjordan]], on the east bank of the [[Jordan River]], to the borders of Jericho in the West Bank. Most of its residents are descendants of the al-Masa'id tribe and immigrants from [[Tammun]] to the north.<ref name=\"ARIJ\">[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/vprofile/Al%20Jiftlik_en_FINAL.pdf Al Jiftlik Village Profile]. [[Applied Research Institute-Jerusalem]] (ARIJ). 2012.</ref>\n\nThe village's name is derived from the [[Turkish language|Turkish]] word ''[[Chiflik (Ottoman Empire)|chiflik]]'', the term for \"land tenure\" in the late [[Ottoman Empire]] which was applied in this as in many other Ottoman locations.<ref name=\"Eini486\"/> It received its name due to the agricultural nature of the village.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/> During the [[Mandatory Palestine|mandate period]], there was a [[Tegart fort]] known as the Jiftlik Police Post just west of the present village.<ref name=\"Eini486\">{{cite book | author = Roza El-Eini | title = Mandated landscape : British imperial rule in Palestine, 1929-1948 | page = 486 | isbn = 978-0-7146-5426-3 | publisher = Routledge | year = 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]], and after the [[1949 Armistice Agreements]], Al-Jiftlik came under [[Jordanian annexation of the West Bank|Jordanian rule]].\n\nSince  the [[Six-Day War]] in 1967,  Al-Jiftlik  has been  under [[Israeli occupation of the West Bank|Israeli occupation]]. In the aftermath of the war over 800 homes in al-Jiftlik were razed by the [[Israel Defense Forces|Israeli army]] and its 6,000 inhabitants were ordered to leave. Most of al-Jiftlik's inhabitants, however, returned to the village.<ref>[[Ghada Karmi|Karmi, Ghada]] (1999). ''The Palestinian Exodus, 1948-1998''. [[University of London]], Centre of Islamic and Middle Eastern Law. Garnet & Ithaca Press. p.90. {{ISBN|0-86372-244-X}}.</ref> \n\nAfter the [[Oslo II Accord|1995 Accords]]  between the Israel and the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] (PLO), the village was designated as part of [[West Bank Areas in the Oslo II Accord#Area C|Area C]]. This makes it subject to full [[State of Israel|Israeli]] military and civil administration.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>  This has allowed the Israelis to commit what  [[Robert Fisk]] in 2010 called  \"ethnic cleansing via bureaucracy\". According to the head of the village council in Jiftlik, Palestinian requests for building were denied or delayed for years, and anything built without permission was \"ruthlessly\" torn down by the Israelis.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/in-the-west-banks-stony-hills-palestine-is-slowly-dying-1883669.html In the West Bank's stony hills, Palestine is slowly dying In the richest of the Occupied lands, Israeli bureaucracy is driving Palestinians out of their homes.] Robert Fisk, [[The Independent]], 30 January 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2005 a [[village council (Palestinian Authority)|village council]] was established to administer local affairs. Its nine members are appointed by the Palestinian National Authority. The council maintains a permanent headquarters and owns a waste collection vehicle. Among its responsibilities are building water and electricity networks in al-Jiftlik and providing an ambulance for the village.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>\n\n==Land confiscations by Israel==\nAccording to [[Applied Research Institute\u2013Jerusalem|ARIJ]], Israel has confiscated land from Al-Jiftlik in order to construct several [[Israeli settlement]]s:\n*2,209 [[dunam]]s were taken for [[Masua]],<ref name=ARIJ17>[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/vprofile/Al%20Jiftlik_en_FINAL.pdf Al Jiftlik Village Profile] p. 17, ARIJ</ref>  \n*1,464  dunams were taken for [[Ma'ale Efrayim]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*1,294 dunams were taken for  [[Yafit]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*645 dunams were taken for  [[Argaman]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*514 dunams were taken for  [[Gitit, Bik'at HaYarden|Gitit]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*438 dunams were taken for  [[Mekhora]],<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n*176 dunams were taken for  [[Petza'el]].<ref name=ARIJ17/>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn the 2007 census al-Jiftlik had a population of 3,546 with exactly 50% being males and the other 50% females. The total number of households was 578 who lived in 692 housing units. The principal clans in al-Jiftlik are the 'Arab al-Masa'id, [[Jahalin Bedouin|'Arab al-Jahalin]], 'Arab al-Ayed, al-Ajajrah, Abu Sureis, Abu Dalakh, Abu Dheila, al-Annuz, al-Rutimat and al-Nafei'at. According to the [[Applied Research Institute-Jerusalem]] (ARIJ), about 100 families have left al-Jiftlik since the start of the [[Second Intifada]] in 2000.<ref name=\"ARIJ\"/>\n\n==Economy and education==\nLike several other villages in the Jordan Valley area, al-Jiftlik is subject to Israeli restrictions on construction and movement, and most often requests for building permits are denied. The village lacks electricity and water infrastructure.<ref>[http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=555337 Aid agencies tread gingerly in Area C]. ''[[Ma'an News Agency]]''. 2013-1-13.</ref> It has primary school managed by the [[United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East|UNRWA]] with 950 students.\n\n==Id'eis==\nId'eis is a Palestinian community several kilometres south of Al-Jiftlik, close to the Masua Israeli settlement. In May 2014, there were 23 families in two neighboring compounds made up of 13 families consisting of 75 people in 15 residential structures living in the north-west compound and 10 families consisting of 53 people living in 14 tents in the southern compound. Each compound also has many livestock structures for their flocks of several thousand sheep and goats. The community makes its living from shepherding and settled in the present location in 1982 having left the Hebron area and migrated across the Jordan Valley as they searched for pastureland. On 21 May 2014, the southern compound was demolished by five Israeli Civil Administration bulldozers supported by IDF soldiers and Border Police on the basis that the families did not have building permits.<ref name=b20140529>{{cite web|title=Civil Administration demolishes nearly half the homes in community of Id\u2019eis, the Jordan Valley|url=http://www.btselem.org/planning_and_building/20140529_demolition_in_ideis_community|publisher=B'tselem|date=29 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.palestinecrops.ps/articleen.aspx?ano=9 Photo of dates grown at Al-Jiftlik on the Palestine Crops website]\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/factsheet/Al%20Jiftlik_FS_EN.pdf Al Jiftlik Village (Fact Sheet)],(Fact Sheet)],  [[Applied Research Institute - Jerusalem]] (ARIJ)\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/vprofile/Al%20Jiftlik_en_FINAL.pdf Al Jiftlik Village Profile], ARIJ\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/images/english/Al-jiftlik_ap_en.jpg Al Jiftlik Arial photo], ARIJ\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/needsfordevelopment/Jiftlik_N_EN.pdf Locality Development Priorities and Needs in Jiftlik], ARIJ\n*Survey of Western Palestine, Map 15:   [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8377  IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.15.jpg Wikimedia commons]\n\n{{Jericho Governorate}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jiftlik, Al-}}\n[[Category:Jericho Governorate]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1950]]\n[[Category:Villages in the West Bank]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of the State of Palestine]]\n", "name_user": "Zarcademan123456", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Jiftlik"}
